{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_dolphin_ver01/data/sn84020665/00514154880/1948081001/0543.xml":{"full_text":"Vol. 1, No. 86\nPalmer, Alaska, August 10, 1948\nTen Cents\nThe annual spilling of the waters of Lake George is pictured in these scenes. The event, which took place during the\nPas* week, each year swells the waters of Knik River many feet above its normal level. The river is fed by the lake which lies\nat the face of Knik Glacier. During 51 weeks of the year the lake is ice-locked at its mouth, but during the annual break-up\nthe waters channel their way through the glacier ice which blocks their exit and rush through narrow gorges and over rapids\na* uPPer .rea-he.s ,of Knik River. The photo to the left is an aerial view of the ice-locked river channel. The broad expanse\nof Knik Glacier is visible in the picture to the right, with the ice^ capped waters of Lake George lying before it. The broad black\nstrip winding down the glacier is a moraine or mound of debris which is pushed ahead of an advancing glacier. In this instance\nthe strip marks the meeting place of two glaciers. (Photos by Palmer Photographic Center).\nWarne Plans\nValley Visit\n\nWilliam E. Warne, assistant\nsecretary of 1he interior, will be\na visitor in Palmer and the Mat\nanuska Valley next Wednesday,\nit was learned this week. Secre\ntary Warne is flying to Anchor\nage on Tuesday to meet with\nGovernor Gruening and mem\nbers of the Alaska Development\nBoard to confer on the Terri\ntory\u2019s housing problem.\nOther members of Secretary\nWarne\u2019s party will include:\nH. Rex Lee, assistant director\nof the division of territories and\ninsular possessions, Kenneth J.\nIladow of Juneau, E. Glen Wil\nder and Wendall Kay of the\nAlaska Housing Authority.\nAfter leaving the Valley on\nWednesday, the party will pro\nceed to Healy to inspect the coal\nfields there. They are due in\nFairbanks on Friday and then\nwill make a five-day inspection\ndrive down the Alaska Highway.\nThe states officials are scheduled\nto return to Washington, D. C.\nAug. 20.\nMeeting Is Postponed\nBecause of the absence of sev\neral committee members, the in\ncorporation study group made no\nprogress on property evaluation\nat last Friday\u2019s meeting. The\ncommittee had been scheduled to\nn^eet at 3 o\u2019clock in the office of\nC. W. Peters. Committee chair\nman W. C. Mau is expected to\ncall the group together in special\nsession some evening this week,\n4 in order to conclude the property\nevaluation.\nTo Go Outside\nMr. and Mrs. Lionel Hawkin\nson and their three sons, who are\nnow residing in Anchorage, are\nleaving for the states soon. They\n\u2019plan to go first to Seattle and\nthen to North Dakota and Minn\nesota. Mrs. Hawkinson will be\nremembered as the former Esther\nLarson of Palmer.\nTuberculosis Rate Here Is\n3 Times Greater Than States\nThe incidence of tuberculosis\nin Alaska is from three to four\ntimes greater than the average\nrate in the United States. This\nfact has been developed from\nthe two-year x-ray survey of\nAlaska, on which Dr. C. Earl Al\nbrecht. territorial commissioner\nof health, recently has made a\nreport.\nFrom records on the 45,000\npersons x-rayed since 1946, it was\nI found that an average of four\npersons in every hundred of\nthose examined showed evidence\nof tuberculosis. The average in a\nsimilar survey in the United\nStates would be from one to two\npersons in every hundred exam\nined.\nIn figures released for 19 of\nIhe territory's cilies, Palmer\nand the Malanuska Valley\nwere found fo have fhe lowest\nrate of any reported. Only 1.2\nper cent of those examined in\nthe Valley area showed evi\ndence of tuberculosis. 1,516 x\nrays were made in the Valley.\nPetersburg also showed the\nsame low percentage figure.\nHighest percentage revealed in\nthe survey was the 23.2 figure of\nKotzebue. Bethel also was far up\nWeils Have Guests\nMr. and Mrs. Emil R. Weil of\nNorth Platte, Neb., and Mr. and\nMrs. Alex Cox of Corpus Christi,\nTex., are visiting the Alvin Weil\nfamily at the Experiment Station.\nThe visitors drove to the Terri\ntory over the Alaska Highway,\narriving here after an eight-day\ntrip. They expect to conclude\ntheir visit in time to sail on the\nAleutian which leaves Seward on\nSept. 9.\nBreaks Her Arm\nDarlene Stephanson recently\nwas confined to the Valley Hos\npital for several days while un\ndergoing treatment for a broken\narm.\non the list with 17.3 per cent.\nSurveys have been continuing\nfor the past two years, but Dr.\nAlbrecht estimates that the job\nis still less than half done. Re\ncent appropriations have increas\ned the personnel, equipment and\nhospitals within Alaska which\nare concerned with the control\nof tuberculosis.\nDr. Albrecht reports that the\nmass x-ray program is uncov\nering many active cases of tu\nberculosis which otherwise\nwould have remained un\nknown. The survey has almost\ndoubled the number of cases\nreported annually by physi\ncians and nurses.\nThe x-ray units used in the\nprogram are carried to Alaskans\nby sea, air, motorcar and rail.\nThe motorship Hygiene serves\nthe coastal area from Southeast\nern Alaska to the St. Lawrence\nIslands. A mobile truck unit car\nries the program to residents liv\ning along the net of highways in\nthe Interior. A portable unit is\ncarried by boat, train, truck and\nplane to areas in Southeastern\nAlaska, along the Railbelt, and\nalong the Arctic Ocean and the\nBering Sea.\nJust Sew Club Meets\nAll members of the Just Sew\n4-H Club, which is led by Mrs.\nGuy Warnica, are expected to\nmeet with Miss Marilyn Johnson\nat the Extension Office next Mon\nday afternoon. Meeting time is\nat 3 o\u2019clock. Club members are\nrequired to bring all their sewing\nprojects with them.\nMOTHER VISITS\nWASILLA\u2014Mrs. Evan Jones,\nmother of Mrs. Walter Teeland,\nis planning a stateside visit soon.\nShe will visit her two daughters,\nMrs. Fritz Visger of Kennewick,\nWash., and Mrs. Jack Bennett of\nLincoln, Neb. Mrs. Jones expects\nto leave sometime late this\nmonth.\nThe curtain has fallen on Lake\nGeorge\u2019s annual first night. The\nclimax to the natural drama,\nin which the Lake and Knik Gla\ncier are starred, came at about\n3 o\u2019clock last Thursday after\nnoon. Then flood waters reached\ntheir peak, according to measure\nments taken from Knik River\nbridge on the Anchorage-Palmer\nhighway.\nAn element of mystery was\ninjected into this year\u2019s show,\nfor one measurement taken\nThursday morning shortly before\nnoon, showed a drop in the height\nof the waters. Subsequent meas\nurements, which were taken at\nabout two-hour intervals on\nThursday, proved that recession\nto be only temporary for the\nwaters continued to rise until\nlater that afternoon.\nMembers of the U. S. Geologi\ncal Survey crew and Kirk Stone\nof the geography department of\nthe University of Wisconsin, who\nconducted the measurement\ntests, cannot explain the momen\ntary drop. It is possible that one\nmeasurement was faulty, they\nconcede. If that was not the case,\nthey have no explanation.\nZero hour measurements show\ned the river was still rising at\nl 2:05 p.m. Thursday. The measure\nment taken at this hour was the\nlast to show an increase in the\nheight of the floodwaters. In\na measurement taken at 4:20 that\nafternoon, waters had dropped\nthree-fourths of an inch.\nThe recession came even more\nrapidly than the flood, accord\ning to later measurements. The\nriver was returning to its normal\nflow at the rate of a two-foot\ndrop every 24 hours, according\nto subsequent measurements.\nThis year, the first in which\nany scientific measurements have\nbeen obtained during the sea\nsonal dumping of Lake George,\nwas uneventful, in comparison to\nsome in former years. Lake\nGeorge drained gradually this\nyear without the wholesale flood\ning of lands bordering Knik\nRiver, which has occurred in oth\ner years.\nThe scientists who conducted\n(Continued on Back Page;\nLegion Post\nTo Sponsor\nMagician Show\nSomething new and different\nin the way of entertainment for\nPalmer is planned by the local\npost of the American Legion.\nCommander Jack Maze announc\ned this week. On the evening of\nAug. 21, Michael Cain, famous\nmagician, is to perform in the\nlocal gymnasium.\nMr. Cain has a two-hour show\nof feats of magic. He has just\ncompleted a very successful tour\nin the states. From Aug. 17 to\nAug. 20, the magician will be in\nAnchorage, where he will pre\nsent four shows.\nHighlight of the two-hour show\nis an astonishing trick in which\nthe magician, in three seconds,\nspirits a girl assistant from a\nroped and padlocked trunk on\nthe stage. Before the audience\nthe girl is locked in the trunk,\nafter being tied in a large bag.\nThe trunk is roped shut and then\nplaced behind a screen while\nsomeone counts three. When the\npadlocked trunk is opened, the\ngirl has disappeared and another\nstage assistant, who has been\npresent on the stage during the\nearly preparation of the stunt, is\nrevealed in her place. This act\nclimaxes a show which has many\nunusual tricks of magic.\nMr. Maze states that he be\nlieves the Michael Cain show to\nbe the first of its kind in Palmer.\nIt is presented under auspices of\nthe Legion with the proceeds to\nbe earmarked for the local post\u2019s\nbuilding fund.\nTickets for the show now are\non sale at the North Palmer\nStore, Matanuska Valley Bank,\nKetchikan Spruce, and the Co-op.\nMeanwhile the Legion plans\nfor the construction of a hall are\nprogressing well, according to\nMr. Maze. He said it is hoped\nconstruction of a basement can\nbegin this week. The hall will be\nerected on the Legion lots across\nfrom the Matanuska Hotel.\nThe Legion commander prom\nised further information on the\nbuilding plans of the local post\nwithin the next few days. Speci\nfications must be approved be\nfore a definite announcement of\nplans can be made, he said.\nNew Alaskan Directory\nIs On Stands Again\nPalmer business establish\nments are well represented in\nthe recent issue of the Alaska\nBusiness Directory, which ap\npeared on the stands this week.\nThe Directory is an annual pub\nlication issued by Tewkesbury\nPublishers.\nThere are 14 local firms whose\nplaces of business are pictured\nin the pages of the latest guide.\nPalmer is discussed in several\nplaces, where Alaskan resources\nare mentioned.\nThe book, in addition to much\nhelpful information on all phases\nof Territorial life, gives a com\nplete index, listed by topic, of\nall business establishments in the\nTerritory. It also carries adver\ntisements of businesses conduct\ned in Alaskan cities.\nDaughter Born to Zehrungs\nA baby daughter was born to\nMr. and Mrs. Carl Zehrung at\nthe Valley Hospital last Saturday.\nThe little girl weighed seven\npounds, two ounces.","height":"22608","width":"14908"}}
